We could merge these two. `if constexpr` would be fine, because this caster already depends on C++17. My first attempt was:

```c++
static PyObject* unicode_from_fs_native(const std::filesystem::path::string_type& w) {
    if constexpr (std::is_same_v<std::filesystem::path::string_type, std::string>) {
        return PyUnicode_DecodeFSDefaultAndSize(w.c_str(), ssize_t(w.size()));
    } else if (!std::is_same_v<std::filesystem::path::string_type, std::wstring>) {
        return PyUnicode_FromWideChar(w.c_str(), ssize_t(w.size()));
    }
}
```

That doesn't work, because the compiler can still see that `w.c_str()` doesn't match both `char*` and `wchar_t*`. So we have to make it a template...

```c+
template<typename T = std::filesystem::path::string_type>
PyObject* unicode_from_fs_native(const T& w) {
    if constexpr (std::is_same_v<T, std::string>) {
        return PyUnicode_DecodeFSDefaultAndSize(w.c_str(), ssize_t(w.size()));
    } else if (std::is_same_v<T, std::wstring>) {
        return PyUnicode_FromWideChar(w.c_str(), ssize_t(w.size()));
    }
}
```

The problem with the above is that we really don't want `T` to be deduced - we want the default to always apply. The language calls this a [non-deduced context](https://eel.is/c++draft/temp.deduct.type#5) and `std::type_identity_t<T>` is exactly a non-deduced `T`.

```c++
template<typename T = std::filesystem::path::string_type>
PyObject* unicode_from_fs_native(const std::type_identity_t<T>& w) {
    if constexpr (std::is_same_v<T, std::string>) {
        return PyUnicode_DecodeFSDefaultAndSize(w.c_str(), ssize_t(w.size()));
    } else if (std::is_same_v<T, std::wstring>) {
        return PyUnicode_FromWideChar(w.c_str(), ssize_t(w.size()));
    }
}
```

This version finally works, but `std::type_identity<T>` is C++20... Final result, with type identity reimplemented, can be found here: https://godbolt.org/z/hPYdq7

