I have test `hasattr(self._modified_class, "__init__"):`. There will some test test case failure. If a class is derived from `object`, it will have a `__init__` function from object. In this case, the `hasattr(self._modified_class, "__init__")` will be true, but `_method_signatures` will not contain "__init__". 
```python
@ray.remote
class Foo(object):
def method(self):
    pass
```

I went ahead and made this method const, since I personally like the operational definition of "does not change the behavior of future method calls".

In this case, there's no need to mark any data structures as mutable, given C++ semantics. (I don't like relying 100% on the compiler to define const, since the following compiles:
```
class foo {
public:
  int read() const { return *x_; } 
  void increment() const {  // O RLY?
    *x_ += 1;
  }
private:
  int* x = new int(0);
};
```
