[self.assert_structure()](https://github.com/DataDog/dd-trace-py/blob/4313f388383b90ccf2bcbca9d7ef1c400c827ece/tests/utils/span.py#L367) is pretty cool.

```python
self.index.search(....)

self.assert_span_count(1)
self.assert_structure(dict(
    service='algoliasearch',
    name='algoliasearch.search',
    span_type=SEARCH_SPAN_TYPE,
    error=0,
    meta={
        'query_args.attributes_to_retrieve': 'firstname,lastname',
    },
    metrics={
        'processing_time_ms': 23,
        'number_of_hits': 1,
    },
))
```

To ensure extra meta doesn't end up in `meta`/`metrics`, you can do:

```python
self.assert_structure('same as above but without meta or metrics')
root = self.get_root_span()

# Assert these and only these attributes exist in `meta`
root.assert_meta({
    'query_args.attributes_to_retrieve': 'firstname,lastname',
}, exact=True)
root.assert_metrics({

}, exact=True)
```

These are all fairly new patterns that haven't been adopted by every test suite yet.

